Author: James Clancey <james.clancey@gmail.com>
Date:   Wed Jul 22 21:12:09 2026 -0700

    fix(engine): guard GetUnitVariable against destroyed-unit SIGSEGV
    
    When a unit is fully released, CUnit::Release() clears Orders (Orders.clear()).
    A Lua trigger that held the old slot number could then call GetUnitVariable(),
    which called UpdateUnitVariables() -> CurrentOrder() -> Orders[0].get() on an
    empty vector, producing a SIGSEGV.
    
    Observed on the private test map (2)pytest-sync-stress.smp: the shared gold
    mine could be destroyed by incidental catapult/ballista fire while the trigger
    `GetUnitVariable(shared_mine, "ResourcesHeld") <= 0` was still live.
    
    Fix:
    - Check unit->Destroyed before calling UpdateUnitVariables in CclGetUnitVariable.
      Destroyed is set before Orders.clear() in the release path, so this guard
      prevents the out-of-bounds Orders[0] access.
    - Push nil explicitly (matching the existing nullptr sentinel contract) and
      always clean up the pushed unit-value from the Lua stack.
    
    Also:
    - Add test_script_unit.cpp: regression tests for the destroyed-unit nil path
      and the existing sentinel-(-1) nil path.
    - Link macOS frameworks for stratagus_tests so the test binary links on Apple.
    
    Co-authored-by: Copilot App <223556219+Copilot@users.noreply.github.com>
